<Author>A_memberSouthWestUK
<Content>More like a hostel than a comfy hotel. Stayed at this hotel for a long weekend in March 07. Taxi from the airport cost about 鈧?0.A little disappointed upon our arrival. The reception and breakfast area are all in one room! There is no bar in this hotel. The breakfast was very disapppointing. On offer - peach juice, tea, coffee, cereals, cakes and pastries. Sounds ok when you write it down, but was all looking very sad and stale. They seemed to have run out of spoons most mornings.The room photos on the internet are very misleading. The room itself (a double) was the smallest, most cramped hotel room we have ever been in. When asked to upgrade to a bigger room, was told by the receptionist that the hotel was full, and the other rooms were of a similar size anyway. Wardrobe suitable for one persons belongings only. Nowhere to keep suitcase (if you kept it on the floor then that was all the available floor space taken!).The room had little natural daylight, as the shutter outside the window was broken, and couldn't be raised more than a quarter of the height of the window. Nothing to see outside anyway except a brick wall! We were at the back of the hotel, so our room was lovely and quiet to sleep in, with no noise from passing traffic etc. We had asked for a non smoking room, but the stale smell and ashtrays in the room suggested otherwise.The hotel info strongly advises that you use the room safe for valuables, but they do charge you to do this, and ask for a 鈧?0 deposit!The bathroom was shockingly small. So much so that you couldn't actually open the door to get in there, as the toilet was behind it.You could stand in the shower, clean your teeth over the sink, and flush the loo all at the same time!Was clean, but bathroom fittings a little dated.The hotel is within walking distance from the Segrada Familia. For all other sightseeing, Metro station Clot was just across the road from the hotel. It's easy to get a taxi from outside the hotel, we never waited more than a couple of minutes.This was our first time in Barcelona, so we asked the receptionist where to go for food on our first night. She recommended us to Port Olympico area. Very pretty as this was the marina, but sadly touts stand outside every single restaurant, and you cannot stroll without being accosted every 30 seconds. Not for us, so we left with empty stomachs and headed for the (less touristy!) Gothic Quarter, which had some great tapas restaurants. Despite several warnings about pickpockets, bag snatchers  muggings, we had no trouble at all from anyone, even on the Metro.Overall the rooms were suitable for single occupancy only, ok to use as a hostel to sleep in, but don't expect a sumptuous stay! 
